# Architecture Boundaries

Three roots under `src/`:

- `01-service-stack/` — Core pipeline. Messages flow top-to-bottom: Transport → Identity → Classifier → Queue → Worker → Action Router.
- `02-supporting-services/` — Called by the Worker or feed the Queue. Never call each other. Never reach back into the stack.
- `03-connections/` — Documentation only. Describes how services interact. No code lives here.

## Bounded Services

Each numbered folder is a bounded service. A service owns its behavior, its types, and its documentation. Services never directly import runtime code from another service — the Worker orchestrates all cross-service coordination.

## Data Flow Invariants

- All inbound data enters through the Queue — human messages, scheduled events, external data. No exceptions.
- The Worker pulls one item at a time, calls supporting services, then hands the result to the Action Router.
- Action Router decides: Dispatch (send now via Transport), Hold (batch via Scheduler), or Store (save via State).
- Adding a new data source feeds the Queue. It never requires changes to dispatch logic.

## Messaging Invariants

- One shared messaging identity, no name, no app — phone-native texting only.
- Threads are defined by participants, not topics. Five threads total.
- Responses stay in the thread they came from.
- Proactive messages route to the narrowest appropriate thread.

## Resilience Invariants

- The system runs on a single local machine. It must handle downtime gracefully.
- On startup after downtime, stale items are logged silently — never dispatched late.
- Escalation timers and confirmation expiries that passed during an outage are reconciled on startup, not fired late.
- Network failures retry with backoff. Items queue locally until connectivity returns. Nothing is dropped.
- Redis AOF and SQLite WAL mode are required — a crash must not lose queue state or persistent data.
